The GC-MSD and GC-FID (insert) chromatograms of rosemary oil.
The tea tree essential oil contained both light monoterpenes and numerous sesquiterpenes. The
main compound is 4-terpineol, followed by γ-terpinene, 2-carene, α-terpineol, α-terpinene, α-pinene,
o-cymene, limonene, β-caryophyllene, eucalyptol, and β-myrcene—Figure 4. Standards ask for
α-terpinene (5%–13%), which was not found in our tee tree sample, instead 2-carene was found in
high amounts of about 10%. Aromadendrene and δ-cadinene, mentioned by standards in amounts
varying from traces up to 7%–8% were confirmed in the studied sample.
